import cv2 as cv
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1) Load color image
img_path = "/Users/mohsin/MCA/Assignments/Computer Vision/istockphoto-168521971-612x612.jpg"
img_bgr = cv.imread(img_path)
assert img_bgr is not None, "Image not found at given path"
img_rgb = cv.cvtColor(img_bgr, cv.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

# 2) Grayscale + Otsu threshold (invert so coins -> white)
gray = cv.cvtColor(img_bgr, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
_, thresh = cv.threshold(gray, 0, 255, cv.THRESH_BINARY_INV + cv.THRESH_OTSU)

# 3) Morphological opening to remove small white noise
kernel = np.ones((3, 3), np.uint8)
opening = cv.morphologyEx(thresh, cv.MORPH_OPEN, kernel, iterations=2)

# 4) Sure background via dilation
sure_bg = cv.dilate(opening, kernel, iterations=3)

# 5) Sure foreground via distance transform + threshold
dist_transform = cv.distanceTransform(opening, cv.DIST_L2, 5)
_, sure_fg = cv.threshold(dist_transform, 0.7 * dist_transform.max(), 255, 0)
sure_fg = sure_fg.astype(np.uint8)

# 6) Unknown region (bg - fg)
unknown = cv.subtract(sure_bg, sure_fg)

# 7) Marker labeling + Watershed, then superimpose boundaries on original
_, markers = cv.connectedComponents(sure_fg)
markers = markers + 1
markers[unknown == 255] = 0
markers = markers.astype(np.int32)
cv.watershed(img_bgr.copy(), markers)
overlay = img_rgb.copy()
overlay[markers == -1] = [255, 0, 0]  # red boundaries

# 8) Display steps + final result
# Distance transform visualization (normalized)
dist_vis = cv.normalize(dist_transform, None, 0, 255, cv.NORM_MINMAX).astype(np.uint8)

titles = [
    "Original (RGB)", "Grayscale", "Otsu Threshold",
    "Opening (noise removed)", "Sure Background (dilation)", "Distance Transform",
    "Sure Foreground", "Unknown Region", "Watershed Overlay"
]
images = [img_rgb, gray, thresh, opening, sure_bg, dist_vis, sure_fg, unknown, overlay]
cmaps  = [None, "gray", "gray", "gray", "gray", "gray", "gray", "gray", None]

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 14))
for i, (im, title, cmap) in enumerate(zip(images, titles, cmaps), 1):
    plt.subplot(3, 3, i)
    if cmap:
        plt.imshow(im, cmap=cmap)
    else:
        plt.imshow(im)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.axis("off")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpretation (concise):

  • Otsu threshold automatically selects a cutoff, turning coins (objects) white and the light background black after inversion. This creates a binary mask.
  • Opening removes tiny bright specks and separates close boundaries slightly, improving the masks cleanliness.
  • Dilation (sure background) expands black regions, ensuring we have confident background pixels.
  • Distance transform peaks at object centers; thresholding it gives sure foreground that avoids edges (so touching coins wont be merged yet).
  • Unknown region is the boundary band between foreground and background where labels are uncertain.
  • Markers + Watershed grow labels from the sure foreground into the unknown region while respecting background, producing clean boundaries. Red lines in the overlay show the final watershed ridges between touching coins.
  • Result quality: Good separation where coins touch slightly; performance depends on illumination and contrast. Overly bright specular highlights or heavy shadows could require a different kernel size or the foreground threshold factor (0.7) to be tuned.
